def draw_cm( actual, predicted ):
    cm = metrics.confusion_matrix( actual, predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True,fmt='.2f', xticklabels = [0,1] , yticklabels = [0,1] )
    plt.ylabel('Observed')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted')
    plt.show()

# different solvers 

recall_values =[]
train_score=[]
test_score=[]
solver = ['newton-cg','lbfgs','liblinear','sag','saga']

for i in solver:
    model = LogisticRegression(random_state=42,penalty='l2', C = 0.75,solver=i,max_iter=5000)  # changing values of solver
    model.fit(x_train, y_train) 
    model_predict = model.predict(x_test)

    train_score.append(round(model.score(x_train, y_train),3))
    test_score.append(round(model.score(x_test, y_test),3))

6. Give Business understanding of your model? (5 marks)¶

The objective of this excercise is to predict whether the customer will take personal loan or not.

Since we are interested in the customers who had actually bought personal loans, but our model predicted that they will not buy loan. so the goal is to reduce False Negatives. Looking at our confusion matrix, we need to look at recall performance parameter along with accuracy.

Looking at exploratory data analysis, the 'Income', 'CCAvg' and 'Education' information seems to be more significant for deciding personal loan.

Using default parameters of LogisticRegression,we get following performance parameters Training accuracy : 0.908 Testing accuracy: 0.908 TP = 1318 TN = 44 FP = 33 FN = 105 Recall: 0.2953020134228188 Precision: 0.5714285714285714 F1 Score: 0.3893805309734513 Roc Auc Score: 0.6354378312857988

We performed following steps to improve model performance

  1. Use Scaled Data
  2. Experiment with differnet solvers
  3. Change max_iter (This may cause performance delay in real world application but did not cause significant problem for our case)
  4. Experiment with C values

Our final model includes

  1. Scaled Data
  2. solver='liblinear'
  3. penalty='l1'
  4. max_iter=5000
  5. C=0.75

We improved performance parameters as follows

Training accuracy: 0.9531428571428572 Testing accuracy: 0.9486666666666667 TP = 1334 TN = 89 FP = 17 FN = 60 Recall: 0.5973154362416108 Precision: 0.839622641509434 F1 Score: 0.6980392156862745 Roc Auc Score: 0.7923660822954909

One observation is that the 'Training accuracy' is slightly better than 'Testing accuracy'. This may indicate overfitting of the model but same is observed with different parameters.

This is our understanding from confusion matrix with final model

  1. True Positives (TP): Our model correctly predicted that 1334 customers will not take personal loan

  2. True Negatives (TN): Our model correctly predicted that 89 customers will take personal loan

  3. False Positives (FP): Our model incorrectly predicted that 17 customers will take personal loan

  4. False Negatives (FN): Our model incorrectly predicted that 60 customers will not take personal loan
